TY  - JOUR
T1  - Investment and Competitive Matching
AU  - Nöldeke, Georg
AU  - Samuelson, Larry
Y1  - 2015/05/01
PY  - 2015
DA  - 2015/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA12349
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 835
EP  - 896
VL  - 83
IS  - 3
KW  - Matching
KW  - competitive matching
KW  - investment
KW  - positive assortment
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA12349
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We study markets in which agents first make investments and are then matched into potentially productive partnerships. Equilibrium investments and the equilibrium matching will be efficient if agents can simultaneously negotiate investments and matches, but we focus on markets in which agents must first sink their investments before matching. Additional equilibria may arise in this sunk-investment setting, even though our matching market is competitive. These equilibria exhibit inefficiencies that we can interpret as coordination failures. All allocations satisfying a constrained efficiency property are equilibria, and the converse holds if preferences satisfy a separability condition. We identify sufficient conditions (most notably, quasiconcave utilities) for the investments of matched agents to satisfy an exchange efficiency property as well as sufficient conditions (most notably, a single crossing property) for agents to be matched positive assortatively, with these conditions then forming the core of sufficient conditions for the efficiency of equilibrium allocations.
ER  - 

